OAS-COM-101 — Communications and Public Engagement Operations Standard Operating Procedure (SOP)

Canonical Designation: OAS-COM-101
Status: Canonical Draft v1.0
Authority: OAS-COM-002 — Communications Governance and Public Engagement Framework
Owner: Chief Communications Steward
Effective Date: July 13, 2026
Review Cycle: Annual

---

Purpose

This Standard Operating Procedure establishes the canonical process for internal communications, member communications, public communications, publication workflows, communication approvals, stakeholder engagement, and day-to-day communications operations throughout Aureus.

Its purpose is to ensure communications remain accurate, timely, coordinated, transparent, constitutionally aligned, and capable of strengthening institutional trust while faithfully advancing Aureus' mission.

---

Scope

This procedure applies to:

- Internal communications
- Member communications
- Public communications
- Publication workflows
- Communication approvals
- Stakeholder engagement
- Communication scheduling
- Communications monitoring
- Communications reporting
- Communications documentation

---

Objectives

Communications operations shall:

- Advance the mission.
- Protect members.
- Preserve constitutional alignment.
- Promote truthful communication.
- Strengthen institutional trust.
- Encourage respectful engagement.
- Improve operational consistency.
- Enable continuous improvement.

---

Roles and Responsibilities

Communications Steward

Responsible for:

- Coordinating communications.
- Managing publication workflows.
- Supporting stakeholder engagement.
- Monitoring communications performance.
- Preparing governance reports.

---

Content Owners

Responsible for:

- Preparing communication content.
- Verifying factual accuracy.
- Following brand standards.
- Maintaining documentation.
- Supporting communication reviews.

---

AI Communications Steward

Responsible for:

- Organizing publication schedules.
- Preparing communication summaries.
- Monitoring communication metrics.
- Supporting accessibility improvements.
- Producing communications analytics.
- Assisting administrative workflows.

Human stewards remain responsible for official communications, publication approvals, media statements, policy interpretation, and governance decisions.

---

Prerequisites

Before communications activities begin:

- Communication purpose is defined.
- Intended audience is identified.
- Required approvals are assigned.
- Applicable communication standards are available.

---

Procedure

Step 1 — Communication Planning

Document:

- Purpose.
- Audience.
- Key messages.
- Delivery method.
- Responsible stewards.
- Publication timeline.

---

Step 2 — Content Preparation

Prepare communications according to:

- Constitutional principles.
- Brand standards.
- Editorial guidelines.
- Accessibility standards.
- Institutional policies.

Verify factual accuracy before publication.

---

Step 3 — Review and Approval

Review communications for:

- Accuracy.
- Clarity.
- Constitutional alignment.
- Brand consistency.
- Appropriate approvals.

Record all required approvals before publication.

---

Step 4 — Publication

Publish communications through approved channels.

Maintain publication records and communication history.

---

Step 5 — Stakeholder Engagement

Support engagement by:

- Responding respectfully.
- Providing accurate information.
- Recording significant feedback.
- Escalating unresolved issues.
- Encouraging constructive dialogue.

---

Step 6 — Monitoring

Monitor:

- Audience engagement.
- Communication effectiveness.
- Publication performance.
- Feedback trends.
- Accessibility.
- Improvement opportunities.

---

Step 7 — Continuous Improvement

Improve communications through:

- Editorial reviews.
- Audience feedback.
- Steward feedback.
- AI-assisted analysis.
- Governance evaluations.
- Lessons learned.

---

Success Metrics

Monitor:

- Publication timeliness.
- Communication accuracy.
- Audience engagement.
- Accessibility compliance.
- Stakeholder satisfaction.
- Brand consistency.
- Governance compliance.
- Mission support.

---

Exceptions

Emergency communications may require expedited approval procedures while maintaining documentation and retrospective governance review.

---

Documentation

Maintain:

- Communication plans.
- Publication records.
- Approval records.
- Stakeholder feedback.
- Communications metrics.
- Editorial reviews.
- Governance reports.
- Improvement plans.

---

Continuous Improvement

Communications operations shall improve through editorial assessments, stewardship feedback, AI-assisted analysis, governance evaluations, audience reviews, and lessons learned.

